Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @baking potato{1} and @sweet potato{1} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop them on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with @olive oil{}, then season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> Use two baking trays if necessary, you want the potatoes nicely spread out.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest the @lemon{1/2} and finely chop the @chives{1}.

> You can snip the chives with scissors if it's easier.

Drizzle the @sea bass fillets{2} with the @olive oil{} for the marinade. Season with @salt{} and half the @Cajun spice mix{1/2}, @Cajun spice mix{}.

> Don't use all of the Cajun spice for the marinade!

Rub this onto both sides of the fish. In a #small bowl{}, mix the remaining Cajun spice with half the chives, a pinch of lemon zest, a squeeze of lemon juice and the @olive oil{2%tbsp} for the dressing. Season with salt and keep to one side.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Stir-fry the @chopped cavolo nero{100%g} until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> Add a splash of water and cover with a lid if necessary to help them along.

When softened, add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Season with salt and pepper to taste. Transfer to a large #bowl{} and cover with foil to keep warm. Wipe the frying pan clean with some #kitchen paper{}, we'll use it to fry the fish.

Heat your (now empty) frying pan on medium-high heat (no oil). Add the sea bass to the pan skin side down and cook until the skin is golden brown, ~{2-3%minutes}, then turn over and cook for a further ~{2%minutes}.

> Don't move the fish while it's cooking skin side down or you won't get a crispy skin! The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

When the potatoes are cooked, add them to your bowl of greens and mash roughly with a #potato masher{} (or a fork). It won't be smooth but it will be delicious - we call this a 'smash'. Mix in a knob of @butter{knob}(if you want things extra delicious) and the remaining chives. Season to taste with salt and pepper. Serve your smash on plates topped with the fish and a drizzle of dressing. Enjoy!